<section id="philosophy">
    <h2>Key Arguments</h2>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>Core Thesis</h3>
        <blockquote>
            "A calorie is not a calorie. The source matters. Fructose is metabolized differently than glucose - it goes straight to the liver where it's converted to fat, drives insulin resistance, and causes metabolic syndrome. This is the real cause of the obesity and heart disease epidemic."
        </blockquote>
    </div>

    <h3>The Fructose Problem</h3>
    <p>Dr. Lustig's key insight is that fructose (half of table sugar) is metabolized differently than other sugars:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Liver-only metabolism:</strong> Unlike glucose, fructose can only be processed by the liver</li>
        <li><strong>De novo lipogenesis:</strong> Excess fructose is converted directly to fat</li>
        <li><strong>No satiety signal:</strong> Fructose doesn't trigger insulin or leptin properly, so you stay hungry</li>
        <li><strong>Uric acid production:</strong> Fructose metabolism raises uric acid, causing gout and hypertension</li>
        <li><strong>Fatty liver:</strong> Chronic fructose consumption causes non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>The "Processed Food" Hypothesis</h3>
    <p>Dr. Lustig argues that it's not just sugar, but the entire ultra-processed food system that's causing disease:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Fiber has been stripped from foods, removing the natural "brake" on absorption</li>
        <li>Added sugar makes low-quality food palatable and addictive</li>
        <li>Industrial processing destroys nutrients while adding harmful compounds</li>
        <li>The food industry has engineered products to maximize consumption, not nutrition</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>The Alcohol Parallel</h3>
        <p>Dr. Lustig famously compares fructose to alcohol: both are metabolized only by the liver, both cause fatty liver, and both can drive metabolic disease. The difference? We don't give children alcohol, but we give them juice boxes full of fructose.</p>
    </div>
</section>

